{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620569"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:44:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:44:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16636"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16636"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.08,0.22,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76655"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9327"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62152"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"5061"},{"type":"tags","id":"5178"},{"type":"tags","id":"5198"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22390"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76655"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner requesting help to quit smoking. She has previously tried nicotine replacement therapy without success. She also reports symptoms of low mood. The doctor considers prescribing bupropion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of bupropion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks noradrenaline and dopamine reuptake","Inhibits serotonin transporter function","Antagonises nicotinic acetylcholine receptors","Blocks dopamine receptor signalling","Inhibits monoamine oxidase enzyme"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBupropion primarily works by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking noradrenaline and dopamine reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E in the central nervous system. This increases the concentration of these neurotransmitters in the synaptic cleft, enhancing both noradrenergic and dopaminergic neurotransmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits serotonin transporter function\u003C/strong\u003E: unlike selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors, bupropion has minimal effect on serotonin neurotransmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonises nicotinic acetylcholine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: while bupropion may have some weak nicotinic receptor effects, this is not its primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks dopamine receptor signalling\u003C/strong\u003E: bupropion increases dopamine availability rather than blocking its effects at receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits monoamine oxidase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of monoamine oxidase inhibitors, which is distinct from bupropion\u0027s action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe dual action on noradrenaline and dopamine explains bupropion\u0027s effectiveness in both depression and smoking cessation. The dopaminergic effect is particularly important for reducing nicotine cravings and withdrawal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bupropion acts primarily by inhibiting noradrenaline and dopamine reuptake in the brain.","Unlike selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors, bupropion does not significantly affect serotonin neurotransmission.","Bupropion is effective for both depression and smoking cessation due to its dopaminergic effects."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62152"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16636"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62152"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:21:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:22:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9327"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76655"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links"